        "content": "<p>Suppose that I want to define HOL as a theory in Pure.  I might begin by defining the object-level equality operator = with some associated axioms.  Then as a next step I could define True as (λx.x = λx.x).</p>\n<p>Here's my attempt to do that:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Isabelle\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">theory</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hello</span>\n<span class=\"kp\">imports</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Pure</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">begin</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">typedecl</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">formula</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">judgment</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">trueprop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">::</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"formula ⇒ prop\"</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"s\">‹_›</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">5</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">axiomatization</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">eq</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">::</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"formula ⇒ formula ⇒ formula\"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"kp\">infixl</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">‹=›</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">50</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kp\">where</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">refl</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"t = t\"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kp\">and</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">subst</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"s = t ⟹ P s = P t\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">definition</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">true</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">::</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">formula</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kp\">where</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"s\">\"true ≡ ((λx. x) = (λx. x))\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">end</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>However, the definition of true above fails to type check.  That's because = expects two formulas, yet (λx. x) isn't a formula - it's a pure term of type 'a -&gt; 'a.</p>\n<p>So somehow I need λx. x to have type formula, but I don't see how to achieve that.  HOL/HOL.thy has</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Isabelle\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">definition</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">True</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">::</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">bool</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"kp\">where</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"True ≡ ((λx::bool. x) = (λx. x))\"</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>so it works there, but doesn't in my minimal example.  What am I missing?</p>",
        "id": 579543574,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Dingle",
        "timestamp": 1773576913
